rhead absorption rate using different bases such as direct labour hours, direct materials cost, direct labour cost, prime cost, machine hours, and units of output. It also includes calculating the full absorption cost of a product.\"", "\"ACTIVITY-BASED COSTING (ABC)\":Activity-Based Costing (ABC) is a costing methodology that assigns costs to activities based on their use of resources, applicable in both service and manufacturing industries. This approach provides more accurate cost information by linking costs to specific activities and focusing on the activities that incur costs. ABC involves tracing resource consumption and costing final outputs by identifying cost drivers, which are used to attach activity costs to outputs. Overhead and indirect costs are assigned to related products and services through this method, ensuring a detailed and precise allocation of costs.", "\"TRADITIONAL ABSORPTION COSTING\":Traditional absorption costing is a method where overhead costs are allocated to products based on a single cost driver, such as labor hours or machine hours. This method typically uses direct labor hours or machine hours to apportion all overhead costs between products. For instance, in the case of the Deluxe model, the overhead cost would be only 20% more than that of a Basic model. However, this method may not accurately reflect the true product overhead costs, especially in modern factories with significant overhead costs.", "\"COST DRIVER\":\"A cost driver is a factor that can cause a change in the cost of an activity. In ABC, cost drivers are used to apportion overhead costs to products based on the use of activities by each product.\"", "\"DIRECT LABOUR HOURS\":\"Direct labour hours\" are determined through time and motion studies to establish the most efficient production method and standard hours for job completion. Additionally, direct labour hours serve as a basis used in both re-apportionment and absorption to allocate costs based on the number of hours worked by direct labour.", "\"MACHINE HOURS\":\"Machine hours\" refer to the total number of hours that machines are operated during the production process. They are used as a basis for both re-apportionment and absorption to allocate costs based on the number of hours machines are in operation. In traditional absorption costing, machine hours are often employed as the single cost driver to allocate fixed production overheads. Additionally, machine hours can act as a limiting factor in production, as seen in the context of month 1.", "\"PARTS MOVEMENTS\":\"Parts movements is a basis used in re-apportionment to allocate costs based on the number of parts moved or handled.\"", "\"VARIABLE OVERHEADS UTILIZED\":\"Variable overheads utilized is a basis used in re-apportionment to allocate costs based on the variable overheads consumed.\"", "\"DIRECT MATERIAL COST RATE\":\"Direct material cost rate is a basis used in absorption to allocate costs based on the cost of direct materials used.\"", "\"DIRECT LABOUR COST RATE\":\"Direct labour cost rate is a basis used in absorption to allocate costs based on the cost of direct labour.\"", "\"PRIME COST PERCENTAGE RATE\":\"Prime cost percentage rate is a basis used in absorption to allocate costs based on a percentage of the prime cost.\"", "\"UNIT OF OUTPUT RATE\":\"Unit of output rate is a basis used in absorption to allocate costs based on the number of units produced.\""], "parameters": {"model": "text-embedding-3-small", "temperature": 0.0, "frequency_penalty": null, "presence_penalty": null, "top_p": 1.0, "max_tokens": 4000, "n": 1}}